sec.p:
FPB test measures the pure bending response of a structure. The following five types of specimens were prepared and tested for this analysis.


the neat sandwich beam;

sandwich beam with 5.1 cm (2″) long cavity;

sandwich beam with top and bottom cavity walls reinforced with [0/90]2S AS4/3501-6 carbon/epoxy sheet;

sandwich beam cavity filled with 32.0 kg/m3(2 lb/ft3) expandable foam; and

sandwich beam cavity filled with 80.1 kg/m3(5 lb/ft3) expandable foam.

TPB test measures the bending and shear response of a structure. The following six types of specimens were prepared and tested for this analysis.


the neat sandwich beam;

sandwich beam with 5.1 cm (2″) long cavity;

sandwich beam cavity filled with 80.1 kg/m3(5 lb/ft3) dense expandable foam;

sandwich beam cavity reinforced at the corners with aluminum angles and filled with 80.1 kg/m3(5 lb/ft3) dense expandable foam;

sandwich beam cavity reinforced at the corners with aluminum angles and filled with 240.3 kg/m3(15 lb/ft3) dense expandable foam; and

sandwich beam cavity filled with 240.3 kg/m3(15 lb/ft3) dense expandable foam.

The heat pipes were considered for the current thermal management due to their advantages compared to other solutions. The main advantages of heat pipes are:


relatively light weight;

passive cooling;

high temperature endurance; and

widely used and proven for the reliability in in many aerospace applications.
